### Recommendation: Use `TimeProvider` (.NET 8+)

.NET 8 ships a built-in [`TimeProvider`](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.timeprovider) abstract class. Inject it via DI instead of calling `DateTime` statics:

```csharp
// Registration
services.AddSingleton(TimeProvider.System);

// In your classes — inject it
public class OrderProcessor(ILogger<OrderProcessor> logger, TimeProvider timeProvider)
{
    public Order CreateOrder(string customerId, decimal amount)
    {
        var now = timeProvider.GetUtcNow().UtcDateTime;
        var order = new Order { ..., CreatedAt = now, ExpiresAt = now.AddDays(30) };
        // ...
    }

    public bool IsExpired(Order order) =>
        timeProvider.GetUtcNow().UtcDateTime > order.ExpiresAt;
}
```

In tests, use the built-in fake:

```csharp
var fake = new Microsoft.Extensions.Time.Testing.FakeTimeProvider(
    new DateTimeOffset(2026, 1, 15, 0, 0, 0, TimeSpan.Zero));

var processor = new OrderProcessor(logger, fake);
var order = processor.CreateOrder("cust-1", 99m);

Assert.Equal(new DateTime(2026, 1, 15, 0, 0, 0, DateTimeKind.Utc), order.CreatedAt);

fake.Advance(TimeSpan.FromDays(31));
Assert.True(processor.IsExpired(order));
```

> The `FakeTimeProvider` lives in `Microsoft.Extensions.TimeProvider.Testing` (NuGet package for your test project).

### Other issues spotted

1. **Line 25 uses `DateTime.Now`** (local time) while everything else uses UTC — likely a bug.
2. **`File.WriteAllText`/`File.AppendAllText`** and **`new HttpClient()`** are also untestable statics — consider abstracting file I/O behind `IFileSystem` and injecting `IHttpClientFactory` as a follow-up.

